3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bybit calculates SEI/USDT funding rates every 8 hours using the interest rate differential and premium/discount between the perpetual price and spot index. The funding fee is exchanged directly between long and short position holders, with no exchange commission. Bybit's unified trading account allows seamless margin management across spot and derivatives positions. The exchange uses a robust price discovery mechanism that incorporates multiple spot exchanges to ensure fair funding rate calculations."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SEI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SEI represents a high-performance Layer 1 blockchain optimized for DeFi applications, making it attractive for funding rate arbitrage due to its moderate volatility and growing ecosystem adoption. The pair typically exhibits higher funding rates during bullish DeFi cycles and lower rates during market downturns. Bybit's strong derivatives infrastructure and competitive fees make it an optimal venue for capturing SEI funding rate premiums."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SEI/USDT funding rates on Bybit have historically ranged from -0.05% to +0.15% per 8-hour period, with average rates hovering around +0.02%. During major DeFi rallies, funding rates often spike above +0.08% as leveraged long positions dominate the market. Conversely, during broader crypto selloffs, funding rates frequently turn negative as traders short SEI against stronger Layer 1 alternatives. The pair shows distinct seasonality patterns, with higher funding rates typically observed during Q1 and Q4 when DeFi activity increases."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange funding rate arbitrage between Bybit and other venues trading SEI perpetuals can yield consistent returns when rate differentials exceed transaction costs. Delta-neutral strategies involve simultaneously holding long spot SEI and short perpetual positions to capture positive funding payments. Given Bybit's competitive maker fees of 0.02%, the break-even funding rate for profitable arbitrage is approximately 0.04% per 8-hour period. Advanced traders often employ automated systems to monitor funding rate convergence across multiple timeframes and exchanges."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SEI's relatively lower market capitalization compared to established Layer 1s like Ethereum introduces higher volatility risk during funding rate arbitrage strategies. Sudden news events affecting Sei Network's ecosystem can cause rapid price movements that may exceed funding rate gains. Bybit's auto-deleveraging system may trigger position closures during extreme market conditions, potentially disrupting long-term arbitrage strategies. Traders should maintain adequate margin buffers and consider the impact of weekend funding periods when markets may exhibit reduced liquidity and higher basis risk."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"What are typical SEI funding rates on Bybit compared to other Layer 1 tokens?","answer":"SEI funding rates on Bybit typically range 0.01-0.03% higher than established Layer 1s like DOT or ATOM due to its smaller market cap and higher retail interest. This premium often makes SEI funding rate arbitrage more profitable but also introduces additional volatility risk."},{"question":"How does Bybit's 8-hour funding schedule affect SEI arbitrage strategies?","answer":"Bybit's 8-hour intervals (00:00, 08:00, 16:00 UTC) provide more frequent funding payments compared to some exchanges using daily schedules. This allows for faster capital turnover in SEI arbitrage strategies but requires more active position management and higher transaction frequency."},{"question":"Can I use Bybit's unified account for SEI spot-perp arbitrage?","answer":"Yes, Bybit's unified trading account allows seamless execution of delta-neutral SEI strategies by holding spot SEI while shorting SEI/USDT perpetuals. The unified margin system automatically calculates net exposure and margin requirements across both positions."},{"question":"What minimum capital is recommended for SEI funding rate arbitrage on Bybit?","answer":"Given SEI's volatility and Bybit's minimum position sizes, effective funding rate arbitrage typically requires at least $5,000-10,000 to maintain proper risk management and capture meaningful returns after transaction costs. Smaller accounts may struggle with position sizing flexibility."}]}]
